[1
Date: Sat 15 Jul 2000
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Kyodo News, 14 Jul 2000 [edited


Seven die, 75 infected by dengue fever in Bangladesh
----------------------------------------------------
Dengue fever is spreading at an "alarming rate" in Dhaka, virologists,
doctors and hospital sources in the Bangladeshi capital said Friday. At
least 75 cases of dengue fever have been detected in hospitals in the city
in the last week, the sources said. Seven patients, including 2 children,
have died in the last 2 weeks.
Prof. Nizoral Islam, head of the Virology Department at Bangabandhu Medical
University Hospital and a member of a WHO Expert Advisory Panel on Viral
Disease, described the situation in Dhaka as alarming. "The sudden
emergence of dengue-carrier mosquitoes in a crowded city such as Dhaka
worries us very much because mosquito habitation is growing unchecked," the
professor said.
According to the World Health Organization, worldwide cases of dengue
infection are increasing dramatically. In Bangladesh, it is considered as a
re-emerging disease. Globally, 50 million cases of dengue infection are
[estimated to occur annually.
