[3
Date: Fri, 21 Jul 2000 12:20:02 -0400
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: Xinhua News Agency, filed 21 Jul 2000 4:38 AM EST [edited

Dengue/DHF - Bangladesh (Dhaka) - Appeal for help
--------------------------------------------------
The Bangladeshi government has sought international help for diagnosis and
treatment of dengue fever which was said to have assumed an alarming
proportion, the Bangla-language daily Ittefaq reported here Friday. Quoting
laboratory sources, the daily said at least 10 people were killed by the
disease in the capital alone in two weeks, and around 60 percent of 500
patients have been tested dengue positive. The reagents essential to test
dengue have been exhausted, the sources told the newspaper. Prof. Nazrul
Islam of Virology Department and Prof. Ruhul Amin of Microbiology
Department of Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujib Medical University said they have
run out of reagents. Health Minister Sheikh Fazlul Karim Selim said steps
have been taken to bring reagents from abroad through the World Health
Organisation (WHO). Reports from different hospitals and clinics throughout
the Dhaka city suggested that dengue fever is spreading at an alarming
rate.
A WHO report said Southeast Asia and western Pacific regions are the areas
where dengue fever has taken the most serious turn. Before 1970, only nine
countries had experienced DHF (Dengue hemorrhagic fever) epidemics, but the
number had increased fourfold by 1995. Some 2.5 billion people worldwide
are at risk of catching dengue fever.
